<Author>travelwise
<Content>Great Value and Location The Regencia Colon is a great budget option if you want to be situated in the heart of the Barri Gotic. The hotel itself is located right behind its more expensive sibling, the Colon so it is just steps from the Cathedral Plaza. Nicely decorated and well maintained, the hotel is up a set of about six or seven steps and has an excellent elevator. Half a short block away is Laitana, a major street running toward the harbor, and just on the other side of that is the Born with its restaurants, shops, and nightlife. If you cross the Cathedral Square in the other direction, you are in the heart of some great Barri Gotic shopping streets, the hot chocolate cafes on Calle Petritxol, and Las Ramblas (just a half block from the Boqueria). If you head away from the Cathedral, you will quickly come to the Placa Catalunya, about two to three blocks from the hotel.If you take the Aerobus from the airport to the last stop at Catalunya, you simply need to walk down Portal del Angel to the Cathedral Square, turn left, and then left again at the end of the Colon and you will be at the Regencia Colon (about ten minutes). There is a taxi stand across Laitana so it isn鈥檛 necessary to call cabs unless you need someone to pull in front for heavy bags. I always told taxis to take us back to Laitana, circa del Catedral, (very easy) and that got us right around the corner.I stayed in this hotel twice, once for a long weekend before a cruise and then for another long weekend at the end. The two rooms which I was given, 556 and 557, were next to each other on the fifth floor (which I had requested) and close to the corner where there is a partial view of of the Cathedral Square (and lots of light but not a view of the Cathedral). The rooms were identical, mirror images of each other. Decorated in chintz, each came equipped with two beds, a desk, a minibar with room to put a couple of water bottles, a safe, a place to hang clothes with very limited drawer space, and a desk chair. The room was certainly decently sized and perfectly adequate. The fifth floor has tiny balconies outside the rooms on this side of the hotel. The balconies are miniscule, but you can step out and check the weather. There are shutters on the doors which can be lowered to keep out light and the hotel uses old fashioned metal keys, which are kept at the desk. The bathroom was small, but also perfectly fine. It contained a hair dryer, a tub with shower, toilet and bidet. Everything worked. Toiletries provided included a shampoo/conditioner, shower gel, soap, and toothpaste/toothbrush kits, shower cap, and a shoe-shine cloth.The safe was quirky but worked. Instructions say to press the red button on the back of the door to reset the combination. Unfortunately, there is no red button and when you press the button that is there, you need to make sure you press and hold it sufficiently before trying to enter your new code. If you need help, one of the desk guys will come up. There are some differences between the Regencia Colon and a more expensive hotel (I stayed in the NH Duc de la Victoria last year, for example, and found the bed and bedding there of higher quality.) The Regencia Colon lacked Kleenex and there are no robes or slippers. The desk guys (Jose, Luis and David) are all very nice and try to be as helpful as possible. Just know that their knowledge can be limited (especially related to food!) We were given directions to the PANS when we wanted to go to the Bocatta one day. Victor, who does the reservations and is very efficient, seemed to have no knowledge of most of my restaurant requests. I provided him with the telephone numbers and he made the calls (I had written to the hotel several weeks in advance to make the reservations, but they said there had been computer problems and they hadn鈥檛 received the requests.) If you do your homework and simply need help with the map, you鈥檒l be okay or if you want suggestions for the neighborhood, they can help. We also asked for extra towels and pillows and received these without any problem. At these prices you can鈥檛 expect first rate concierge-quality help.As many have commented, the rooms at the front of the hotel are just off the Cathedral Square, which often features loud music blared through speakers and a variety of concerts. The Cathedral clock chimes every fifteen minutes. People can be noisy and the noise seems to carry very easily. We also noted the arrival of the garbage trucks sometime early (or maybe in the middle of the night) on the first morning we were there. The big problem is that the room in November was stifling hot. Since you can鈥檛 control the heat (and apparently once the hotel turns it on, it stays on until the month they turn it off), you are forced to open the doors or windows. While this solves the temperature problem, it means you will need ear plugs if you are a light sleeper. Since I have no trouble going back to sleep, it was a minor problem for me, but I can see how it would be a big problem for others.There is plenty of eating close by. You can walk to virtually all of the Barri Gotic eateries and those in the Born. For breakfast, there is a PANS and a Bocatta two minutes away, Neyras is around the corner, and best of all, the Boqueria is an easy walk away for a memorable breakfast. Don't miss the Boqueria -- it's a fabulous market just for sightseeing.The front desk sells Hop On Hop Off bus tickets for the same price you pay at the Catalunya hub. If you buy at the hotel, you can get on the Blue Route bus right across Laitana and do the entire loop without having to stand on line at Catalunya. If you want the Red Route, you simply transfer at the first transfer point, which is the Gaudi houses 鈥?La Padrera and Casa Bottilo (the first stop for the Red Route). As many have said, the HOHO bus is the best way to do the sights in Barcelona. We paid 26 euros for two consecutive days (the cost is 23 euros for one day at the moment). You can stay on the bus and get an overview, get off at the stops that interest you and ride the buses as many hours as you like. We paid different rates for different nights at the Regencia Colon (it was significantly cheaper at the end of November than it had been two weeks before but I think it also depends on the cruise schedules since many of their clients seemed to be cruisers.) I booked through the hotel website and we paid in euros at the end of each stay, which worked well for us since the value of the dollar was significantly better when we paid than when we booked! On the whole, other than the noise problem, this is an excellent pick if you want to save money and be in a great location. 
