<Content>Bring earplugs, but otherwise pretty great! I can't compare this hotel to others in Barcelona, but I *can* say that since I was mentally prepared for the noise and knew I'd need to sleep with earplugs, I was VERY happy with my stay in all other respects.My favorite things:- The front-desk staff were always very helpful and pleasant. Since I had major jet lag, I can confirm that they were helpful at all hours: day, evening, 2 in the morning, and even 6 in the morning.- The room! I got the absolutely cutest room up on the 5th floor, tucked into a corner, obviously modernized within the past few years and with every touch exactly as I would have designed it. Little stuff that might not sound like it makes much of a difference: A light in the closet! Warm-colored (instead of white) walls! Enough hangers! A built-in stand for your suitcase with trim on the back that helps you keep from dinging up the wall! Extra switches for all the lights next to the bed! A fridge that you can put your stuff in without breaking a seal that brings the Mini-Bar Charge Police! Good, light-blocking shutters! Yummy coconut-scented shampoo  lotion freebies instead of some gross perfume-y smell! And best of all, a satisfying shower that has enough door on it that you don't end up spraying the whole room!- The cleanliness. I couldn't find anything to quibble with, and there were little signs everywhere that the cleaning lady had been there. It's a small enough hotel that there may be one person who does the cleaning, and she seems to take pride in her work.- Location. Really perfect.- Yeah, the breakfast is a bit pricey, but it's also very complete and good, with fresh Spanish cheese and fresh orange slices along with all the usual cereal/toast/coffee/tea stuff. On your first day, it's a perfectly reasonable way to get off to a good start.It's hard to think of any negatives, although if you feel strange sleeping with earplugs in you'll definitely want to stay somewhere else. The only thing I can think of is that although Spain's new anti-smoking law is most definitely respected and enforced, if I left the bathroom window open some second-hand smoke came in that way (maybe from an employee break room below?). I paid just BARELY into the triple digits per night, and I must say I think I got my money's-worth. 
